06135nam a22008295i 9781487541378DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20212021onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814875413787 a10.3138/97814875413782doi  a(DE-B1597)645226  a(OCoLC)1337866459  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aPG3328.Z6bD62843 2021eb 7aLIT0042402bisacsh04a891.73/322300aDostoevsky at 200 :bThe Novel in Modernity /ced. by Katherine Bowers, Kate Holland. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (264 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tNote on Transliteration -- tIntroduction: Dostoevsky and the Novel in Modernity -- t1 The Poetics of the Slap: Dostoevsky's Disintegrating Duel Plot -- t2 Dostoevsky and the (Missing) Marriage Plot -- t3 The Greasy-Haired Pawnbroker and the Capitalist Raskrasavitsa: Dostoevsky's Businesswomen -- t4 Allegories of the Material World: Dostoevsky and Nineteenth-Century Science -- t5 Dostoevsky, Sechenov, and the Reflexes of the Brain: Towards a Stylistic Genealogy of Notes from Underground -- t6 Deferred Senses and Distanced Spaces: Embodying the Boundaries of Dostoevsky's Realism -- t7 Under the Floorboards, Over the Door: The Gothic Corpse and Writing Fear in The Idiot -- t8 The Improbable Poetics of Crime and Punishment -- t9 Illegitimacies of the Novel: Characterization in Dostoevsky's The Adolescent -- t10 Sovereignty and the Novel: Dostoevsky's Political Theology -- tWorks Cited -- tContributors -- tIndex0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aMarking the bicentenary of Dostoevsky's birth, Dostoevsky at 200: The Novel in Modernity takes the writer's art - specifically the tension between experience and formal representation - as its central theme. While many critical approaches to Dostoevsky's works are concerned with spiritual and philosophical dilemmas, this volume focuses instead on questions of design and narrative to explore Dostoevsky and the novel from a multitude of perspectives. Contributions situate Dostoevsky's formal choices of narrative, plot, genre, characterization, and the novel itself within modernity and consider how the experience of modernity led to Dostoevsky's particular engagement with form. Conceived as a forum for younger scholars working in new directions in Dostoevsky scholarship, the chapters that comprise this volume ask how narrative and genre shape Dostoevsky's works, as well as how they influence the way modernity is represented. Of interest not just to readers and scholars of Russian literature, but also to those interested in the genre of the novel more broadly, Dostoevsky at 200 is pathbreaking in its approach to the question of Dostoevsky's contribution to the novel as a form.  afunded by University of Toronto Libraries  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCivilization, Modern, in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Russian & Former Soviet Union.2bisacsh  aCrime and Punishment.  aDostoevskii.  aFyodor Dostoevsky.  aNotes from Underground.  aRussian literature.  aRussian realism.  aThe Idiot.  amodernity.  anineteenth-century.  arepresentation.  athe novel.1 aBerman, Anna A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBowers, Katherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBowers, Katherine, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFrazier, Melissa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHolland, Kate, econtributor.4ctb4http